observations.recommendation:
We recommended the Local Chief Executive to:
a. Direct the Information and Communications Technology Center to post in the LGU websites
the infrastructure projects with the information as prescribed in Section 101 of the GAA 2023;

Recommendations:
We recommended the Local Chief Executive to:
Initiate the One-Time Cleansing of PPE accounts in accordance with COA Circular No. 2020-006, and formally create an Inventory Committee, if not yet established;
Direct the CGSO to conduct a complete physical inventory of all PPE items and submit to the Office of the City Auditor the RPCPPE, following the prescribed format;
Direct the CGSO and City Accountant’s Office to reconcile their records and address any discrepancies in accordance with the applicable accounting standards, and existing rules and regulations; and
Ensure that future PPE inventories are conducted regularly and in compliance with COA guidelines to maintain accurate asset records.

Recommendations:
We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
Direct the City Assessor to expedite the processing of land titles in the name of the City Government of Iligan to prevent potential adverse claims and legal disputes;
Instruct the City Accountant and CGSO to provide a detailed explanation for the discrepancy of ₱4,240,867.02 between their records;
Mandate the City Accountant to secure copies of titles and donation documents for reconciliation with accounting records, ensuring accuracy and compliance with financial reporting standards and to submit the complete Notes to Financial Statements to provide transparency and a clear breakdown of reported balances;
Instruct the City Budget Officer to allocate sufficient funding for the titling and legal processing of these lands, ensuring that financial constraints do not hinder the regularization process;
Require the CGSO to maintain and document all Deeds of Sale, Deeds of Donation, and other land transactions, ensuring traceability of land ownership; and
Direct the City Legal Office to actively assist in resolving legal obstacles affecting the titling of lands, particularly in addressing estate tax concerns, facilitating the issuance of patents, and ensuring legal compliance in land acquisitions. The City Legal Office should provide clear legal guidance and support to the CGSO to expedite the regularization of untitled lands and protect city assets from future claims or encroachments.

Recommendations:
We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
Instruct the City Accountant to derecognize the overstated amount of P27,662,731 from the Breeding Stocks account in accordance with the existing rules and regulations to ensure the fair presentation of the City’s financial statements in accordance with PPSAS 1 and other applicable standards;
Direct the City Agriculturist and City Accountant to conduct a thorough investigation into the missing records and livestock corresponding to the beginning balance, determine the causes of the discrepancy, establish accountability for the misstatement, and submit the results of their reconciliation to COA;
Require the City Agriculturist and CGSO to strengthen internal control measures by enforcing strict documentation and turnover procedures to ensure that all accountable officers properly turn over records, reports, and inventories before separation from service;
Direct the City Agriculturist implement periodic physical inventory of biological assets and reconcile the results with accounting records to prevent similar discrepancies in the future, and submit an annual report on the physical inventory to COA to enhance transparency and accountability; and
Review and enhance policies on asset management to improve oversight, prevent misappropriation, and ensure proper documentation and tracking of government assets.

Recommendations:
We recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct the City Accountant to:
Verify, analyze, and validate all outstanding balances in the Guaranty/Security Deposits Payable account and determine their legitimacy and necessity for settlement;
Reconcile the amounts found in the General Ledger, Schedule of Aging of Payables, and Financial Statements to ensure consistency and accuracy;
Coordinate with concerned creditors to confirm the existence of valid claims and assess whether these payables remain enforceable obligations of the City; and
Prepare the necessary adjusting entries for payables with negative balances to ensure that the financial statements fairly present the City’s actual liabilities in compliance with PPSAS 1, PPSAS 19, and the MNGAS for LGUs.

Recommendations:
We recommended that management:
Implement control measures to avoid instances the accountable officer hold funds in excess of the existing maximum bond accountability e.g assign to other accountable officer the excess accountability for which a separate Fidelity Bond shall be secured;
Determine the necessity of increasing the fidelity bond of the accountable officer to cover their accountabilities;
Direct the collecting officer to update his cashbook daily or upon occurrence of transaction and reconcile the balance with the cash on hand;
Direct the City Accountant to create and maintain Subsidiary Ledgers (SLs) for the Accountable Officers; and
Ensure all Fidelity Bonds of collecting officers are renewed before their expiration and strictly prohibit accountable officers, whose Fidelity Bonds have expired and not been renewed, from collecting and/or possessing government funds.

Recommendations:
We recommended that the City Treasurer to:
Release the long-outstanding and accumulated amount of the unremitted shares of the barangays from its collections;
Strictly ensure that the barangays’ shares from the collections are released to the recipient barangays within the reglementary period;
Require the City Accountant additional schedule on the notes to financial statements to provide breakdown on Due to LGUs account; and
Ensure that the barangays’ shares from the collections are remitted in full and are not subjected to any unjustified lien or holdback for whatever purpose.

Recommendations:
We recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) to:
Direct the City Accountant to conduct a thorough reconciliation of the Financial Statements (FS) and the Electronic New Government Accounting System (e-NGAS) to ensure consistency and accuracy in financial reporting, and submit the revised and corrected FS to COA;
Direct the City Accountant to conduct periodic reconciliations and internal reviews before the submission of financial statements to ensure the completeness and accuracy of the financial statement;
Direct the City Accountant to ensure full compliance with Philippine Public Sector Accounting Standards (PPSAS) and Commission on Audit (COA) regulations by providing complete disclosures on all critical financial accounts in the Notes to Financial Statements; and
Implement stricter oversight and accountability measures to ensure that all financial reporting requirements are met.

Recommendations:
We recommended to the Local School Board to:
Refrain from charging non-priority expenditure against the Special Education Fund;
Evaluate the programs/projects/activities to be included in the SEF budget, taking into consideration the objectives set forth by the provisions of DepEd-DBM-DILG Joint Circular No. 1, s. 2017;
Evaluate the participation of the officers and members of the LSB responsible for the passage of Resolution for approving the Iligan City LSB Annual Budget, which includes donations/aid to BSP and GSP under the Special Programs, and the Audit Team will issue ND on the financial assistance directly given to Boy Scout of the Philippines;
Stop charging Office Supplies / equipment used by the LSB Officials and LGU employees, and drop from the books of accounts – LGU Iligan City those assets transferred to the DepEd and record in the books of DepEd;
Stop charging training expenses. These activities and programs are regular functions of the DepEd. Thus, the expenditures should have been charged against the available funds of the concerned office. The LSB to provide budget allocation of the activity if how much was budgeted by the DepEd, if not sufficient, how much to be shouldered by the LGU charged to SEF;
Stop charging financial assistance for sports activities that lacks a proper channel to identify that the DepEd did not provide a budget for that activity. All requests for financial assistance from the field shall be coursed through the Office of the Schools Division Superintendent, Co-Chairman of the Provincial Local School Board. The requesting official shall submit to the Receiving Section of the DepEd Division Office the additional documentary requirements;
Purchase of library books and periodicals for the libraries of the different elementary and secondary schools in the province, city, and municipality, and purchase of instructional materials, workbooks and textbooks needed by public elementary and secondary schools, should be subject to the prevailing policies and guidelines of the DepEd;
Payment of salaries/wages of utility workers and security guards hired in public elementary and secondary schools which have not been provided such positions in the DepEd budget should submit such certifications;
Payment of the Job orders should not be recorded as CIP. We advised the Management to stop charging Engineering and Administrative Overhead Expenses (EAO) in the local projects; and
Let the recipients which are non-parents on the Busog, Lusog, Talino (BLT) Central Kitchen refund the amount received.

Recommendations:
We recommended to the Local Chief Executive as Chairman of the Local School Board to:
To closely coordinate with the Schools Division Superintendent as Co-Chairman of the Local School Board and its members and properly deliberate the issues on the slow implementation of the programs/projects of the Special Education Fund and evaluate the programs / projects / activities to be included in the SEF budget, taking into consideration the objective set forth by the provisions of DepEd-DBM-DILG Joint Circular No. 1, s. 2017;
Direct the Schools Division Superintendent as Co-Chairman of the Local School Board and its members to submit their programs / projects / proposals of the Special Education Fund with the coordination of the schools involved;
Evaluate the programs / projects / activities included in the continuing appropriations and then reconsider it in the next budget year should its implementations were not feasible;
Monitor the efficient and effective implementation of all programs and projects under the Special Education Fund (SEF); and
Stop charging to SEF those expenditures not allowed, otherwise, Notice of Disallowance will be issued despite services rendered because good faith cannot anymore be reasoned out.

We recommend that the concerned employees go over the JC to gain understanding of the various provisions relative to the utilization of the CF, specifically on the following: (51)
a) Supporting documents of cash advance of CF;
b) Submission of cash advance voucher to the Audit Team;
c) Maintenance of cash disbursement record; and
Liquidation of cash advance.
We further recommended that the Municipal Accountant submit an explanation of why the reported balance of the Advances to Officers and Employees account, which pertains to the cash advance of CF, is understated by ₱1,000.00. (52)

Management to review the number of organic personnel composing the BAC Secretariat so that they will be able to perform their functions/ responsibilities as required in RA No. 9184;

Assign a BAC Secretariat member who shall focus on advertising and/or posting the bidding opportunities; and

Direct the BAC Secretariat to coordinate with the PIO in posting the complete bidding documents, minutes of pre-bid conferences, the NTP and the related approved contracts at the City's website.

The DCW Division strictly enforce the provisions in the Water Service Undertaking to consumers with delinquent accounts until all balances from prior and current years are paid;

Determine past due accounts and include them in the Billing Statements;

Upgrade or fully establish its software system to speed up monitoring delinquent accounts.

We recommended that the Municipal Agriculture officer:   

Trace all the fund sources and programs in the previous years involving the purchase and distribution of breeding stocks so as to fully account the movement of breeding stocks under the custody and monitoring of the Municipal Agriculture Office;

Conduct a complete physical inventory of breeding stocks and prepare an inventory report supplying all the necessary data herein, in order to trace the difference between the "should be" balance per records against the result of the actual count, and have a proper and complete documentation of the inventory of breeding stocks from thereon; 

Furnish the Municipal Accountant a copy of the said report in order to reconcile the report of the Municipal Agriculture Officer with that of the records of the Municipal Accountant and prepare the appropriate documents or certification to support any variance arrived at.

We recommended that Management:

Instruct the DAP Manager to send demand letters to debtor-LGU employees requiring settlement of their accounts and gather data as to those individuals who are not connected with LGU to facilitate sending of demand letters/billing statements;

Instruct the DAP Manager to install more stringent regulations/policies in selling/offering of goods and services on account so as to generate more income to the municipality, to prevent further accumulation of receivables and reduce the risk of non-collection thereof.

We recommended to the Local Chief Executive to:

a. Review the development projects embodied in the annual budget, meticulously and judiciously plan all procurement activities taking into consideration the selection of an ideal period Not Implemented, including a specific timeline Not Implemented;

b. Fast track and expedite implementation of the remaining projects to adequately deliver the basic services to the constituents;

c. Ensure that allocated funds are timely and optimally utilized in accordance with existing guidelines to maximize benefits that intended beneficiaries could derive from the projects;

d. Submit a justification letter for the non-implementation of the projects and management’s plan of action on the matter; and

e. Create a project monitoring committee to aid the management in the evaluation and monitoring of projects to be implemented within the city.

We recommended to the Local School Board to:

a. Refrain from charging non-priority expenditure against Special Education Fund;

b. Evaluate the programs / projects / activities to be included in the SEF budget, taking into consideration the objectives set forth by the provisions of DepEd-DBM-DILG Joint Circular No. 1, s. 2017;

c. Evaluate the participation of the officers and members of the LSB responsible for the passage of Resolution for approving the Iligan City LSB Annual Budget for calendar year 2022, which includes donations / aid to BSP and GSP under the Special Programs;

d. Audit Team will issue ND, if warranted; and

e. Stop engaging in investment – time deposit the Special Education Funds.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive as Chairman of the Local School Board to:

a. To closely coordinate with the Schools Division Superintendent as Co-Chairman of the Local School Board and its members and properly deliberate the issues on the slow implementation of the programs / projects of the Special Education Fund;

b. Evaluate the programs / projects / activities to be included in the SEF budget, taking into consideration the objective set forth by the provisions of DepEd-DBM-DILG Joint Circular No. 1, s. 2017;

c. Evaluate the programs / projects / activities included in the continuing appropriations and then reconsider it in the next budget year should its implementations were not feasible; and

d. Monitor the efficient and effective implementation of all programs and projects under the Special Education Fund (SEF).

