We reiterated our audit recommendations that the LCE -
instruct the Property Officer and Accounting Office to prepare a reconciliation of their records and to perform the cleansing count eventually;
order the Inventory Committee to tag all PPEs with inventory stickers for easy identification;
direct the Accounting Office to exert more effort to reconcile PPELCs with the GLs;
advise the Inventory Committee to conduct an inventory taking for the ensuing year and prepare and submit RPCPPE in accordance with the pertinent provisions of the MNGAS for LGUs.
The Management informed the Audit Team that the audit recommendations on PPE cannot be ensured to be undertaken in CY 2024 because it necessitates additional manpower complement for the concerned offices. The budget for Personal Services (PS) of the Municipality is constrained with the provisions of the Republic Act (R.A.) No. 7160.

We reiterated our audit recommendations that the LCE -
instruct the concerned Offices to be mindful of their duties laid down in the said Circular;
require the Property Officer to come up with the Local Road Inventory and Road Map and Local Road Network Property Card for all roads under the Municipality’s jurisdiction;
require the Accounting Office to exert effort in preparing the necessary records and to disclose information on Road Networks in the Notes to the Financial Statements in accordance with COA Circular No. 2015-008; and
instruct the Municipal Engineer to assist and/or coordinate in the establishment of correct and verifiable Roadwork Network System.
The Management did not confirm that it will implement the audit recommendations in CY 2024 since compliance with the said recommendations entails additional personnel, which is restricted by the PS budget limitation.

We reiterated our recommendation that the LCE instruct the:
Municipal Planning and Development Office (MPDO) to lead the -
monitoring of the implementation of the CDP/LDIP; and
undertaking of prioritization of PPAs so that specific dates of implementation are indicated in the LDIP/AIP; and
Accounting Office to be careful in using accounts in the recognition of transactions;
We also recommended that POWs for the PPAs implemented by the barangays be prepared by the ME and approved by the Punong Barangay and the LCE and consequently, inspection reports should be prepared by the ME and approved also by the two heads of the LGUs concerned before payment to ensure that the POWs are properly prepared, the parties had meeting of minds on the PPAs to be implemented, and that the projects are correctly completed.
We further recommended that the LCE instruct the:
Bids and Awards Committee (BAC), BAC Secretariat, and other concerned officials and employees to submit necessary documents and/or explanations for the audit observations presented in paragraph 7.43;
Concerned personnel to submit an explanation on the determined ineligible PPAs funded by the Development Fund (DF);
Barangays to submit the required documents enumerated in Article 2.B.4 and 2.B.6 of the Memorandum of Agreement (MOA);
Local Project Monitoring Committee (LPMC) and other concerned parties to review and evaluate the stipulations contained in the MOA and effect necessary actions when so warranted.
Accounting Office to review the transactions pertaining to the transfer of funds to barangays and effect necessary journal entries.

We reiterated our recommendation that the LCE:
instruct the Municipal Accountant to -
be cautious in the preparation of accounting entries and reporting of LDRRMF so as not to mislead stakeholders and cause inappropriate decisions;
follow the MNGAS for LGUs in the recognition of procurement of supplies and materials; and
record necessary adjustment for the CY 2020 cash donation received as recommended in the CY 2020 Audit Report;
instruct the LDRRMO to -
act on the compliance with the minimum standards of disaster preparedness; and
design the LDRRMFIP following the prescribed format by indicating the targeted date of implementation of the PPAs;
caution the Municipal Accountant, MBO, and MT not to be remiss in their responsibilities in the monitoring of the LDRRMFs and to reconcile their records immediately and effect necessary adjustments about the erroneous charging of the project Improvement of MDRRM Operation Center;
direct the BAC, BAC secretariat, the Municipal Accountant and the end users to submit explanations on the noted post audit observations in CY 2022 AAR.
We further recommended that:
for future similar transactions, the LCE instruct the concerned officers to attach to the DVs, distribution lists completely indicating necessary details to facilitate the conduct of validation;
the LDRRMO review implemented projects and ensure that only allowable expenses resulting from disaster risk management activities are charged from LDRRMF; and
concerned officers submit explanation or justification on noted deficiencies in paragraph 8.39.

We recommended that the concerned employees go over the JC to gain understanding of the various provisions relative to the utilization of the CF, specifically on the following:
Supporting documents of cash advance of CF;
Submission of cash advance voucher to the Audit Team;
Maintenance of cash disbursement record; and
Liquidation of cash advance.
We further recommended that the Municipal Accountant submit an explanation of why the reported balance of the Advances to Officers and Employees account, which pertains to the cash advance of CF, is understated by ₱1,000.00.

We recommended the Local Chief Executive:
Direct the City Accountant to issue demand letters to:
Notify the concerned officials and employees of their responsibility to settle their unliquidated cash advances. If the settlement is not received, withhold their salaries considering that they have been notified and given more adequate time to liquidate;
Employees who already resigned or transferred to immediately cause the liquidation or settlement of the unliquidated balances;
Request the write-off of the unliquidated cash advance balances of dead employees;
Strictly monitor periodically the submission of liquidation reports to ensure timely accounting thereof to avoid undue accumulation of outstanding cash advances; and
Strictly comply with the provisions of the Circulars of cash advances.

We recommended the following to ensure full liquidation of fund transfers to the barangays and the utilization thereof is in accordance with the purpose of the fund:
Strictly follow the terms and conditions in the Memorandum of Agreement to avoid the accumulation of unliquidated fund transfers to different barangays;
City accountant to issue demand letters (copy furnished the audit team) to the Punong Barangay/Barangay Treasurer for the submission of the required report to liquidate fund transfer;
The Office of the ABC President shall provide the Source Agency (SA) copy furnished to the audit team with the status of the project’s implementation for the SA to validate the implementation of the project in accordance with the MOA;
Do not release funds for multiple projects in a lump sum to encourage individual barangays to immediately liquidate upon completion of the project; and
Refrain from granting/allowing another fund transfer unless the preceding fund transfer has already been settled and proper accounting thereof is made.

We recommended to the Local Chief Executive:
Direct the City Accountant to prepare and maintain Property, Plant, and Equipment Ledger Cards (PPELCs), Real Property Ledger Cards (RPLCs), Construction in Progress Ledger Cards (CIPLCs) to record the details of the PPEs found in the inventory control account in the general ledger; and submit Subsidiary Ledgers in support of the amounts in the General Ledger;
Direct the CGSO to ensure that the deliveries of properties and equipment are immediately recorded in the respective control property cards based on the AIR and other supporting documents;
Direct the City Agriculture Office to submit inventory reports for the breeding stocks, plants and trees because CGSO had no records at all on the receipts, issuances and its balances;
Direct the Local Chief Executive to take full opportunity on the application of the prescribed guidelines and procedures set forth in COA Circular No. 2020-006, particularly the conduct of physical count of PPE, the recognition of PPE items found at the station, and disposition for non-existing/missing PPE items, if any, for the purpose of one-time cleansing of PPE account balances of the LGU; and
Create an Inventory Committee and require them to prepare the Physical Inventory Plan to be approved by the Local Chief Executive, and submit the same to the Office of the Auditor within the prescribed period.

We recommended the Local Chief Executive the following:
Establish a sound internal control system for the proper handling of inventories/supplies. Purchase and utilization should be properly recorded by adequately trained personnel to establish reliable record of inventories / supplies;
Require the end-users to comply with the requirement of submitting copies of perfected contracts / purchase orders to Auditors within five (5) days upon issuance in order to facilitate post audit of financial transactions and notifying the Auditors of the time and date of scheduled deliveries pursuant to COA Circular No. 96-010;
Require the GSO to submit the Acceptance and inspection report within twenty-four (24) hours from the actual delivery;
Require the BAC to complete fill-up of information in the purchase orders;
Require the GSO to maintain stock cards and to record the receipts, issuance, and the balance in the quantities of each supply / inventory which will be the basis for reconciliation of the accounts with the accounting records;
Require the GSO to submit monthly reports of supplies and materials issued and report on the physical count of inventories to the Commission on Audit together with the journal entry vouchers as proof in recording the expense account by the City Accounting Office;
Require the GSO to prepare the requisition and issue slip (RIS) whenever there is an issuance of inventories to the end-user as a basis to determine accountability and responsibility of the person involved in its utilization; and
Require the Accountant to reconcile their records with the GSO as the final result of the inspection conducted.

We recommended the following to the Local Chief Executive:
Require the City Assessor to process the transfer of titles of the Lands in the name of the CGI;
Require the City Budget Officer to provide allocation on the titling of these lands;
Require the City Accountant to secure a copy of these titled and donated lands to reconcile the same with his books or records; and
Direct the CGSO to have always documented / kept records of the Deed of Sale and any deed of transfers and traced these lands.

We recommended the Local Chief Executive:
Direct the City Accountant to issue demand letters to notify the concerned officials and employees of their responsibility to settle their unliquidated cash advances;
Direct the City Legal Officer to impose sanctions under COA Circular No. 96-004 and COA Circular No. 2012-004, if no settlement has been made by the accountable officers despite previous demands;
Direct the City Accountant to strictly monitor periodically the submission of liquidation reports to ensure timely accounting thereof and to avoid undue accumulation of outstanding cash advances; and
Direct the City Accountant to ensure that no additional cash advances are granted to AOs with unsettled balances.

We recommended that the Management instruct:                            

The Municipal Assessor to furnish the Municipal Treasurer with a copy of the Assessment Roll as basis for the collection of real property taxes and for updating the RPTAR/RPTIC, pursuant to Section 6, Chapter 1 Manual on Real Property Appraisal and Assessment Operations;       
The Municipal Treasurer to coordinate with the Municipal Assessor to timely secure a copy of the Assessment Roll from the latter; and furnish the accountant a duly certified list showing the name of taxpayers and the amount due and collectible for the year, in accordance with Section 19 and 20 of the Manual on NGAS, Vol.1;    

The Municipal Accountant draw a Journal Entry Voucher (JEV) to record the debits to the Real Property Tax Receivable/Special Education Tax Receivable and credit to the Deferred Real property Tax Income, based on the certified list furnished by the Municipal Treasurer;

The Municipal Accountant draw adjusting journal entries in order to arrive at adjusted Real Property Tax Receivable /Special Education Tax Receivable and Deferred RPT/SET account balances after analysing the data gathered from the documents furnished by the Municipal Treasurer.

We recommended that Management:

Instruct Municipal Agricultural Officer to gather data on the whereabouts of the animals comprising the account and conducted a complete physical inventory thereof pursuant to Section 124 of the NGAS Manual  Volume I in order to secure the RCPI and;


Enable the Municipal Accountant to make necessary reconciliation and adjustments, to achieve fair presentation of the Breeding Stocks account in the financial statements.

We recommended that Management:

Launch an aggressive policy in the grant and collection of DAP receivables. It is recommended that officials and employees with huge outstanding balances be no longer allowed to avail of any DAP services and/or goods, without paying their previous balances;

Instruct DAP Manager to send demand letters to debtor- LGU employees requiring settlement of their accounts and gather data as it those individuals who are not connected with the LGU to facilitate sending of demand letters/billing statements;

Instruct the DAP Manager to install more stringent regulations/policies  in selling/offering of goods and services on account so as generate more income to the municipality, to prevent further accumulation of receivables and reduce the risk of non-collection thereof.

We recommended that management instruct:        

The Municipal Accountant to exclude as Deposits in Transit, those after cu-off collections on the last working day of the month which were deposited on the succeeding month;    

The Municipal Treasurer to stop the practice of reporting in the Report of Collections  and Deposits (RCD) those deposits which have slips validated on the succeeding month in order;                 

The Municipal Treasurer to explain the absence of machine validation on deposit slips of collections considered as Deposits  in Transit and use of Cash Deposits for the deposit of checks;  

The Municipal Accountant to reconcile the discrepancy of Ᵽ57,888.11 on the amount of outstanding Checks per BRS and List of Outstanding Checks.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive to:

a. Direct the City Accounting Office to closely monitor cash advances and compel all accountable officers to produce without delay their liquidation reports together with the supporting documents, and to further require the immediate refund of all unused cash advances;

b. Direct the officials and employees who are retiring from the government service to settle their cash advances prior to the issuance of a clearance from money and property accountabilities;

c. Direct the Focal Person assign to conduct a thorough review and evaluation of the affected dormant accounts and comply with all the documentary requirements and procedures under COA Circular 2016-005 for the request for write-off of dormant accounts and the disclosure thereof;

d. Conduct regular and periodic verification, analysis, and validation of the existence of the unliquidated cash advances and determine the concerned accountable officers;

e. Prepare the quarterly aging of dormant unliquidated cash advances on a quarterly basis to support the request for write-off as required under Item 7.4 of COA Circular 2016-005;

f. Ensure that all bonding documentary / procedural requirements are complied with prior to the processing of the cash advance;

g. Stop the practice of granting “one time cash advance” to not bonded official which exposes government resources to risk of loss, theft or misuse;

h. Cause the re-orientation of accountable officers and orient officials to be bonded on their respective responsibility and accountability as accountable officers after having assumed the duties of the office to which they are assigned; and 

i. Ensure the bonding of the AOs to secure the amount of money accountability in compliance with the rules and regulations on cash advances as stated in the COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997, PD 1445 and Treasury Circular No. 02-2019 dated April 25, 2019.

